  <section style="background:var(--white);padding:2rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="blog-post">
      <div class="blog-body">
        <h2>Act in This Order. Do Not Panic.</h2>
        <p>A burst pipe in a Liverpool home can release 400 litres of water an hour. The damage a 30-minute delay causes is significant. The steps below are in priority order. Read them now so you know exactly what to do if this happens.</p>

        <div class="blog-warning">
          <strong>If you smell gas at any point, stop everything and call Cadent Gas on 0800 111 999</strong>
          <p>A gas leak takes absolute priority over a water leak. Get everyone out of the property, do not operate any switches, and call the gas emergency line before doing anything else. Once the gas is made safe, call us on 07399 676656.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Step 1: Turn Off the Water at the Stopcock Immediately</h2>
        <p>The stopcock is the first thing you need to find. In most Liverpool properties it is under the kitchen sink. In Victorian terraces it is sometimes in the cellar, under the stairs or near the front door. If you cannot find the internal stopcock, there is an external one on the footpath outside the property boundary.</p>
        <p>Turn the stopcock clockwise to close it. This stops all water entering the property from the mains. If the stopcock is seized or will not turn, call us on 07399 676656 immediately and also contact <a href="https://www.unitedutilities.com/help-and-support/emergencies/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">United Utilities on 0345 672 3723</a> to isolate the supply at the street.</p>

        <div class="blog-callout">
          <strong>Find your stopcock now, before an emergency happens</strong>
          <p>Check where your stopcock is located today while there is no emergency. If it has not been used in years, turn it a quarter-turn now to check it moves freely. A seized stopcock in an emergency is a serious problem. Add the location to your phone contacts so you do not have to search for it at 2am.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Step 2: Turn Off the Hot Water System</h2>
        <p>After stopping the mains supply, turn off your boiler and any immersion heater. This prevents the boiler from firing when there is no water pressure, which can damage the heat exchanger. It also prevents hot water in the cylinder from continuing to flow if the burst is on the hot water side of the system.</p>

        <h2>Step 3: Turn On All Cold Taps</h2>
        <p>Open every cold tap in the property. This drains the remaining water in the system quickly, reducing the amount of water available to continue flooding through the burst. Once the stopcock is closed, this water has nowhere to go except out through the taps and into the drain.</p>

        <h2>Step 4: Limit the Damage While You Wait</h2>
        <p>Once the water is isolated, focus on limiting the damage that has already occurred:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Move furniture, valuables, electronics and documents away from affected areas</li>
          <li>Lay towels or use buckets to collect dripping water</li>
          <li>Take photos and short video clips of all damage before any cleanup. This is important for any insurance claim</li>
          <li>If water is near electrics, switch off the relevant circuit at the consumer unit and call an electrician before restoring power</li>
          <li>Open windows to begin drying the affected area</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Step 5: Call an Emergency Plumber</h2>
        <p>Call us on 07399 676656. We are a 24/7 emergency plumber covering all Liverpool L1 to L40 postcodes with a guaranteed 30-minute response. A real person answers at any hour. We dispatch our own Gas Safe registered engineers immediately. Most burst pipe repairs in Liverpool are completed on the first visit using parts from the van.</p>
        <p>While you wait, stay on the line with us. Our engineers can give you additional guidance over the phone if needed and will confirm the arrival time by text when dispatched.</p>

        <h2>Why Liverpool Properties Are Particularly Vulnerable</h2>
        <p>Liverpool's housing stock includes one of the highest concentrations of Victorian and Edwardian properties in England. These properties frequently have:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>External pipes in uninsulated loft spaces or cellar entries</li>
          <li>Original 100-year-old copper or lead pipework that is reaching end of life</li>
          <li>Pipes running through unheated spaces such as garages and outrigger extensions</li>
          <li>Cold water tanks in uninsulated lofts that are vulnerable to freezing in winter</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Winter is peak burst pipe season in Liverpool. In a cold snap, properties that have not had pipes insulated are at high risk. If you want your Liverpool property assessed for vulnerable pipework before winter, call us to arrange an inspection.</p>

        <h2>What to Tell Your Insurer</h2>
        <p>Contact your home insurer as soon as the immediate emergency is handled. We provide full documentation for insurance claims including:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>A full itemised invoice for all labour and parts</li>
          <li>Photos of the damage and the completed repair</li>
          <li>A written report explaining the cause of the burst</li>
          <li>Attendance confirmation with time and date</li>
          <li>We can correspond directly with your insurer if required</li>
        </ul>
        <p>For guidance on making a home insurance claim, the <a href="https://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/consumer/insurance/making-a-home-insurance-claim/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Citizens Advice home insurance claims guide</a> and the <a href="https://www.abi.org.uk/products-and-issues/choosing-and-buying/home-insurance/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Association of British Insurers</a> both provide clear independent advice.</p>

        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="pf-faq">
          <details class="pf-faq-item"><summary><span class="pf-faq-tag pf-tag-red">URGENT</span>&nbsp; Where is the stopcock in a Liverpool Victorian terrace?</summary><div class="pf-faq-body"><p>In most Victorian terraces it is under the kitchen sink, in the cellar, under the stairs or near the front door. If you cannot find the internal stopcock, there is an external one on the footpath outside the property boundary. Call us on 07399 676656 and we will help you locate it over the phone.</p></div></details>
          <details class="pf-faq-item"><summary><span class="pf-faq-tag pf-tag-orange">COST</span>&nbsp; How much does a burst pipe repair cost in Liverpool?</summary><div class="pf-faq-body"><p>Most burst pipe repairs in Liverpool cost between £80 and £350 depending on the pipe location, size and severity. We provide a written quote before starting any work. Call 07399 676656 and we will give you an indication of the likely cost over the phone after understanding your situation.</p></div></details>
          <details class="pf-faq-item"><summary><span class="pf-faq-tag pf-tag-navy">INSURANCE</span>&nbsp; Will my home insurance cover a burst pipe repair?</summary><div class="pf-faq-body"><p>Most home insurance policies cover escape of water damage. The repair itself may or may not be covered depending on your policy terms. We provide full documentation for your claim. Take photos of all damage before cleanup and contact your insurer as soon as the immediate emergency is resolved.</p></div></details>
          <details class="pf-faq-item"><summary><span class="pf-faq-tag pf-tag-orange">RESPONSE</span>&nbsp; How quickly can you get to me in Liverpool?</summary><div class="pf-faq-body"><p>We guarantee a 30-minute response across all Liverpool L1 to L40 postcodes. Our average arrival time is 28 minutes. A real person answers 24/7. We text you the engineer name and estimated arrival time when dispatched. Call 07399 676656 now.</p></div></details>
        </div>
      </div>

